</table>

<hr class="sep">

<!-- KEY ANTI-INFLAMMATORY PEPTIDES -->
<h2>Key Anti-Inflammatory Peptides</h2>

<p>Several peptides have demonstrated anti-inflammatory activity in preclinical and, in some cases, clinical research. They work through different mechanisms, target different parts of the inflammatory cascade, and vary in their evidence base. Here's what we know about each one.</p>

<!-- BPC-157 Card -->
<div class="cd ct">
  <div class="tg">Tissue Repair &amp; Anti-Inflammatory</div>
  <h3>BPC-157 (Body Protection Compound)</h3>
  <p style="font-size:14px;margin-bottom:0;">A pentadecapeptide derived from human gastric juice, BPC-157 modulates inflammation through the nitric oxide system, downregulates TNF-&alpha; expression, and accelerates tissue repair across every tissue type tested. Its anti-inflammatory effects are secondary to its broader cytoprotective and healing properties, but they're well-documented across 100+ published studies. Unique among peptides for its gastric acid stability, making oral administration viable (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/29060950/">Sikiric et al., 2018</a>).</p>
</div>

<!-- KPV Card -->
<div class="cd cb">
  <div class="tg">Targeted Anti-Inflammatory</div>
  <h3>KPV (Lysine-Proline-Valine)</h3>
  <p style="font-size:14px;margin-bottom:0;">A tripeptide fragment of alpha-melanocyte-stimulating hormone (&alpha;-MSH), KPV is one of the most directly anti-inflammatory peptides available. It inhibits NF-&kappa;B activation, reduces production of TNF-&alpha;, IL-1&beta;, and IL-6, and has shown particular promise in gut inflammation models. A 2021 study demonstrated that KPV-loaded nanoparticles significantly reduced colonic inflammation in IBD mouse models (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/33547935/">Dalmasso et al., 2021</a>). It crosses cell membranes readily and accumulates in the nucleus where NF-&kappa;B operates.</p>
</div>

<!-- LL-37 Card -->
<div class="cd cp">
  <div class="tg">Antimicrobial &amp; Immunomodulatory</div>
  <h3>LL-37 (Cathelicidin)</h3>
  <p style="font-size:14px;margin-bottom:0;">The only human cathelicidin antimicrobial peptide, <a href="/articles/ll-37-antimicrobial-peptide-guide">LL-37</a> plays a dual role in inflammation. It kills bacteria, fungi, and biofilms directly, while simultaneously modulating the inflammatory response to prevent excessive tissue damage. LL-37 neutralizes lipopolysaccharide (LPS), one of the most potent inflammatory triggers, and modulates dendritic cell and macrophage activity. In chronic infections where persistent bacterial presence drives ongoing inflammation, LL-37 addresses both the cause and the consequence (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/24172146/">Kahlenberg &amp; Kaplan, 2013</a>).</p>
</div>

<h3>Thymosin Alpha-1 and Immune Balance</h3>

<p><a href="/articles/thymosin-alpha-1-immune-guide">Thymosin alpha-1</a> (T&alpha;1) is a 28-amino-acid peptide originally isolated from thymic tissue. It's FDA-approved in over 30 countries for hepatitis B and C treatment, giving it a clinical pedigree most peptides lack.</p>

<p>Its anti-inflammatory effect comes through immune modulation rather than direct suppression. T&alpha;1 enhances regulatory T cell function, promotes dendritic cell maturation, and shifts the immune response from a Th1/Th17 pro-inflammatory profile toward balanced Th1/Th2 signaling. In a 2020 study on COVID-19 patients, thymosin alpha-1 treatment was associated with reduced mortality and lower inflammatory markers in critically ill patients (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32425645/">Liu et al., 2020</a>).</p>

<p>This makes T&alpha;1 particularly relevant for autoimmune-driven inflammation, where the goal isn't to suppress immunity but to restore proper regulation.</p>

<div class="d-t">
  <div class="s">Key Distinction</div>
  <p>Most anti-inflammatory drugs suppress immune function broadly. Peptides like thymosin alpha-1 and KPV modulate specific signaling pathways, reducing pathological inflammation while preserving normal immune surveillance. This is the fundamental advantage of the peptide-based approach.</p>
</div>

<hr class="sep">

<!-- MECHANISMS OF ACTION -->
<h2>Mechanisms of Action: How Peptides Reduce Inflammation</h2>

<p>Understanding how these peptides interact with inflammatory pathways helps explain why they can be more targeted than conventional anti-inflammatories. Each peptide hits the cascade at different points, which also explains why stacking multiple peptides can produce additive effects.</p>

